events.name: Initial meeting!
events.description:
Registration is required: gdgcloudwaw1.eventbrite.com

Hello fellow Cloud users!

During keynote at GDG DevFest 2016 we were proud to announce the new organization of Warsaw chapter and the beginning of 2017 is really big challenge for us -  about 25 people in 6 groups are co-organizing events for our community about very specific topics: Cloud, Firebase, Mobile, VR, Web and more to come.

GDG Cloud Warszawa will organize its first event on January 31st, at Google office in Warsaw and we are inviting all Cloud fans out there! Meetings provided by this chapter will focus around Cloud and GCP, but not only from development and operation perspective - remember that you, as a part of community, will decide which topics will be most popular and therefore organized.

We have limited seats available, and we expect they will fill quickly, so we encourage you to apply early if you'd like to attend. Every applicant will be notified of their status a few days before the event, January 31st. If you are intesteted in completing a Codelab we suggest you to bring your own laptop with charger.

Agenda:
6.30pm | Registration & Refreshments
6:45pm | Talk: Jakub Kołakowski - Welcome to GDG and GCP
7:00pm | Talk: Maciej Sawicki - Containers and Kubernetes
7:45pm | Codelabs and networking
9:00pm | Wrap up

Please also join us at our online communities, here at Meetup and also at Facebook, where we will be publishing information about next events.

events.name: NEXT Extended 2017 Warszawa
events.description:
REGISTRATION WITH EVENTBRITE IS REQUIRED (without it you shall not pass through the building's security)

Next ‘17 will be the largest event in Google’s history.
Google Cloud engineers, customers and partners will gather for inspiration and hands on experiences with tools, technologies and services born in the Cloud, including the latest developments from Google Cloud Platform, G Suite, Maps and Devices. Join us at the NEXT Extended 2017 Warszawa to watch it together on the first day and on the second day listen to live techtalks provided by GCP Software Engineers at Google's Office in Warsaw!

Check the agenda: 

8.03 - Wednesday 

17:30 Registration opens + Networking 

18:00 Livestream starts 

21:00 Wrapup

9.03 - Thursday 

17:30 Registration opens + Networking

18:00 Livestream starts

18:45 Techtalk 1: Michał Sapiński - Deep learning, Tensorflow and Google Cloud Machine Learning.
This talk will introduce deep learning that is a very successful sub-field of machine learning. We will also talk about Tensorflow - the most popular ML package on GitHub and Google Cloud Machine Learning that combines the managed infrastructure of Google Cloud Platform with the power and flexibility of TensorFlow.

19:45 Techtalk 2: Marek Biskup - Google Cloud Functions
Google Cloud Functions is a lightweight compute solution for developers to create single-purpose, stand-alone functions that respond to Cloud events without the need to manage a server or runtime environment. 
This talk will introduce you to Cloud Functions and show you a few example applications.

20:30 Codelabs + Networking 

21:00 Wrapup

events.name: Build a mobile app with Firebase
events.description:
Workshop: Build a mobile app with Firebase
In this codelab you will build a Firestore-backed restaurant recommendation Android app. You will learn how to:
Read and write data to Firestore from a Android app
Listen to changes in Firestore data in realtime
Use Firebase Authentication and security rules to secure Firestore data
Write complex Firestore queries.

Workshop will be conducted by Jeff Huleatt

Jeff is a Developer Advocate for Firebase at Google. He’s excited about helping app developers make cool stuff (whether that’s on web, Android, or iOS). For the past two years, Jeff has helped run Firebase support, so if you have questions about any Firebase product, this is your chance to ask! Prior to Google, he was a software engineer working mostly on JavaScript web apps for financial institutions. Jeff has a Bachelor’s in Computer Science and Applied Sciences in Engineering from Rutgers University.

events.name: Cloud Run Club
events.description:
Together with our partner CodiLime we invite you to Cloud Run Club.

Cloud Run Club is a place for developers interested in Cloud Run and other serverless technologies to come together to learn, share ideas, form a community and... RUN! We'll have an overview of the Cloud Run serverless container product, and then do some hands on labs using Cloud Run. For those interested, we'll also actually go for a run after the labs! The fun-run will take place after the workshop, is optional and will be accessible to runners of all levels.

Ronan Mandel is the global program lead for cloud communities in the Google Developer Relations team. He's been with the team since June of 2018, but has been at Google since 2014, previously leading the developer support and appeals programs for Google Play. Prior to joining Google Ronan has led and managed developer programs for over 20 years at companies such as Amazon/Lab126, Verizon Wireless, Adobe, and Openwave/Phone.com.

events.name: How to break the world record for Pi
events.description:
Places amount limited. Mandatory registration: https://www.eventbrite.com/e/how-to-break-the-world-record-for-pi-tickets-63379980227?discount=GDGWarsawEmma

Meet Emma Haruka, world record holder of the most-calculated digits of Pi.
About this Event
Together GDG Warszawa and Google DevReal team, we're hosting Emma Haruka Iwao, Cloud Developer Advocate at Google. She will share the process that took about 4 months and 200 TiB.

Schedule:

19:00 Registration

19.15 Welcome by Katharina Lindenthal and María Encinar, Google DevRel team for CEE.

19:25 A recipe for beating the record of most-calculated digits of Pi - Emma Haruka Iwao, Cloud Developer Advocate at Google

20:10 Q&A and networking

Meet Emma Haruka, world record holder of the most-calculated digits of Pi.
About this Event
Together GDG Warszawa and Google DevReal team, we're hosting Emma Haruka Iwao, Cloud Developer Advocate at Google. She will share the process that took about 4 months and 200 TiB.

Schedule:

19:00 Registration

19.15 Welcome by Katharina Lindenthal and María Encinar, Google DevRel team for CEE.

19:25 A recipe for beating the record of most-calculated digits of Pi - Emma Haruka Iwao, Cloud Developer Advocate at Google

20:10 Q&A and networking

About Emma Haruka Iwao

Fascinated with Pi since she was a child, Emma Haruka Iwao broke in March the Guinness World Records title for most accurate value of pi, calculating 31.4 trillion digits of Pi.

Emma is a developer advocate for Google Cloud, focusing on application developers experience and high performance computing. She will share the process that took about four months and 200 TiB of storage. Record-breaking Pi calculations have traditionally been done on supercomputers and special-made hardware, but we did it on Cloud for the first time. In this talk she will discuss the nature of the calculation, the architecture, challenges and techniques, and of course the brief history of Pi computation.

Calculating Pi has been the speaker's childhood dream and this talk will also explain how the small dream grew to the new world record.

Places amount limited. Mandatory registration: https://www.eventbrite.com/e/how-to-break-the-world-record-for-pi-tickets-63379980227?discount=GDGWarsawEmma

events.name: Meetup with Googlers - Hands on workshop; Using Firebase as a headless CMS
events.description:
Just a few days after Firebase Summit, we will have a chance to host two amazing speakers from Google.

Jeff Huleatt (some of you may remember his excellent last year's workshop about building a mobile App in Firebase).

Jeff works on Firebase at Google, and he is excited about helping app developers make cool stuff on the web! He maintains a number of Firebase's open source repositories, including Reactfire, a library that makes it easy to use Firebase in React web apps.

Benjamin Ferrari-Church

Ben leads the Firebase Rapid Research team, and focuses on the usability of all Firebase products. He's passionate about making sure that Developer tools solve Developer needs and are easy to use. If you've got feedback about any Firebase product he wants to hear it. Before joining Firebase Ben ran a small food businesses while finishing Grad School and still loves to cook and try new flavors so please share your local recommendations.

Agenda:
- 6:30PM start, pre-networking,
- 7:00 Hello and welcome (and a few announcements) ,
- 7:10 Jeff Huleatt
Using Firebase as a headless CMS (30-45 minutes talk + 5 minute Q&A),
- 8:00 snack break,
- 8:30 Benjamin Ferrari-Church
Focus on the user and all else will follow: A quickstart guide to user research (30-40 minutes +5 minutes Q&A)
- 9:15 beer/networking
